<subsection xml:id="subsec3-chap2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Reversible and Nonreversible gate</title>

  <p>
    Since QC is related to a theory of reversible computing, we note that the NOT gate is reversible while the AND gate is not.

  </p>



  <figure xml:id="fig-NonrANDgategateSimple_1">
    <caption>Non-reversible AND gate representation</caption>
    <image source="NonrAND.png" width="50%"> </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    With the circuit in the fig. 2.3.3, we can simulate a non-reversible gate, besides, we keep a copy of the
inputs and add of the <m>x_0âˆ§x_1</m> operation, after it adds previous result to <m>x_2</m>. We fix <m>x_2 = 0</m> and obtain a
non-reversible AND gate. Where <m>\oplus</m> represents the logical exclusive-OR operation, which it is the same
addition modulo two.
Then, we can obtain a reversible version of the circuit if we replace the irreversible parts with their
reversible counterparts.
  </p>

</subsection>

